Freva - Data search and analysis framework for the Community

Common Problem: Finding and accesing Data

Yet another solution: The Freva framework
  • Central
  • Flexible
  • Intuitive
  • Transparent

Why Freva?

  • Developed by and for the modelling community
  • Mature Software (first prototype in 2012)
  • Secure
  • Client - Server architecture Complexity with the Server not the Client (user)
  • Freva doens't pretend to be alone.
    • We do appreciate that there are other tools that try to archieve simlilar objectives.
  • Our metdata harvesting software enables us to collect data from many different sources.
    • So far: We do offer the most complete metadata store.

Excurse: How does it work?

The web User Interface

https://www.gems.dkrz.de/databrowser/

The client library

  • Small python library
  • Comes with a so called Command Line Interfacer scripting
  • Easy to install:
    $: module load gems
$: python -m pip install freva-client
$: conda install -c conda-forge freva-client

The python client:

In[3]:
from freva_client import databrowser

The command line interface:

$: freva-client databrowser --help

Usage: freva-client databrowser [OPTIONS] COMMAND [ARGS]...

  Data search related commands

Options:
  --help  Show this message and exit.

Commands:
  data-overview     Get an overview over what is available in the...
  metadata-search   Search databrowser for metadata (facets).
  data-search       Search the databrowser for datasets.
  intake-catalogue  Create an intake catalogue from the search.
  stac-catalogue    Create a static STAC catalogue from the search.
  data-count        Count the databrowser search results
  user-data         Add or delete user data.

Remote access to data

  • You don't want to / can't work on levante?
  • You have some overseas collaborators that want to access your data?

Stream the data from levante to anywhere with help of the zarr format

In[133]:
from freva_client import authenticate
import xarray as xr
token = authenticate(host="www.gems.dkrz.de", token_file="~/token.json")
data = databrowser(host="www.gems.dkrz.de", flavour="cmip6", mip_era="mpi-ge", variable_id="tas", experiment_id="historical", stream_zarr=True)
uri = list(data)[0]
uri
Out[133]:
'https://www.nextgems.dkrz.de/api/freva-nextgen/data-portal/zarr/5b8ec334-d2c9-536d-9b8e-249bbd34ac23.zarr'
In[136]:
ds = xr.open_dataset(
    uri,
    engine="zarr", 
    storage_options={
        "headers":{"Authorization": f"Bearer {token['access_token']}"}
   })

Some words on authentication

Data access and adding your own metadata is protected. Access via OAuth2 tokens:

  • OAuth2 tokens are like temporary digital keys.
  • You log in once to prove who you are.
  • After logging in, you get a token (a small code) this is your key.
  • The token is only valid for a limited time (like a session ticket).
  • Expired tokens can be renewed.
